<DIV1 N="A" TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000087.tif" N="[1]">
<MILESTONE UNIT="A folio" N="176a:1">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lordinges, herkne&thorn; to me tale!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Lordlingis</I> N. <I>lystni&thorn;</I> ESNC. <I>to m. t.] grete &amp; smale</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is merier &thorn;an &thorn;e ni&yogh;tingale,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;at is</I> EN; <I>It is</I> S; om. C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3">&THORN;at y schel singe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;at]</I> om. ESC. <I>schel] wole &yogh;ow</I> ESNC.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of a kni&yogh;t ich wile &yogh;ow roune,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ich&mdash;roune] &thorn;at hy&yogh;te Beuoun</I> ES; <I>sir Be|uoun</I> N.</NOTE></L>
<L>Beues a hi&yogh;te of Hamtoune,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>B. a h.] That hyght Befys</I> C; <I>&THORN;at was born</I> EN; <I>&THORN;at was lord</I> S. <I>of] in</I> EN. <I>South|hamptoun</I> SN.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6">Wi&thorn; outen lesing<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>oute</I> SC.<Q><L><I>He was ry&yogh;t</I> (om. SN) <I>a stalwur&thorn;e man</I></L><L><I>And manye</I> (<I>kinges londys he</I> (<I>kyngdomes</I> SN) <I>wan</I></L><L><I>To goddys lawe</I> (<I>lawes</I> SN);</L><L><I>He was &thorn;e beste</I> (<I>in any ferde</I> (<I>&thorn;at com in felde</I> SN),</L><L><I>And most wan wi&thorn;</I> (<I>dynt off swerde</I> (<I>spere and shelde</I> (SN)</L><L><I>Be hys lyff</I> (om. S) <I>dawe</I> (<I>dawes</I> SN). </L></Q>add. ESN.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ich wile &yogh;ow tellen al to gadre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;ow&mdash;gadre] telle yow as y can</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at kni&yogh;t and of is fadre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at] &thorn;e</I> ESN. <I>Of hys fadur, that doghty man</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="9">Sire Gii:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;at hy&yogh;te sere Gy</I> EC; <I>&THORN;e good erl sir Gy</I> SN.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Hamtoun he was sire<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>was] lord and</I> add. SN. <I>he w. s.] &amp; of all &thorn;at schyre</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of al &thorn;at ilche schire,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ther of he was lorde &amp; syre</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">To wardi.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vn to</I> E; <I>Hym to</I> SN. <I>That ys so hardy</I> C.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sir&mdash;Hamt.]</I> So A with red ink; <I>Hic in|cipitur Beffs de Hamptoun</I> E; <I>Sir Beuous of Hampton</I> S; <I>Sir Beuys of Hamptone</I> N; om. C.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="2"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lordinges, &thorn;is, of whan y telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Lordlingis</I> N. <I>&thorn;is] &thorn;e</I> E; <I>he</I> C; eerl add. ESN. <I>of w. y] that y of</I> SNC.</NOTE></L>
<L>Neuer man of flesch ne felle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;er was neuere</I> EC; <I>In his tyme</I> SN.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">Nas so strong,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>That was</I> C; <I>Nas noon</I> SN; <I>Halff</I> E.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so he was in ech striue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And so] As</I> ESNC. <I>ech] euery</I> C; <I>a</I> add. E.</NOTE></L>
<L>And euer he leuede wi&thorn; outen wiue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And] But</I> E. <I>out</I> SNC; <I>a</I> add. E.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">17 put before 16 SN.</NOTE></L>
<L N="18">Al to late and long.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Al to] Tyl</I> ESNC. <I>late and] hyt was</I> C.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="3"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan he was fallen in to elde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Whan] &THORN;o</I> ESN. <I>to]</I> om. SN.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne mi&yogh;te him self welde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>When he myght not</I> C. <I>be-welde</I> E.</NOTE></L>
<L N="21">He wolde a wif take;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A wyff wolde he</I> (om. E) <I>take</I> EC.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sone &thorn;ar after, ich vnderstonde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And sone</I> SN; <I>And</I> C. <I>&thorn;ar]</I> om. SC. <I>after] as</I> add. C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Him hadde be leuer &thorn;an al &thorn;is londe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He</I> C. <I>be]</I> om. SC. <I>betere</I> E. <I>&thorn;is] his</I> ESC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">Hadde he hire for-sake.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He hadde here</I> ESC.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>An elde a wif he tok an honde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In age</I> C. <I>A wyf in elde</I> SN. <I>A wyff he took in eelde</I> E. <I>an] yn</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e kinges dou&yogh;ter of Scotlonde,</L>
<L N="27">So faire and bri&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So] Ful</I> E.</NOTE></L>
<L>Allas, &thorn;at he hire euer ches!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>euere he here</I> ESC.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hire loue his lif a les<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For&mdash;lif] Hys owne</I> (<I>lyf for her</I> (<I>hed &thorn;er|fore</I> E) ESNC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">Wi&thorn; mechel vnri&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>muche</I> S.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is maide ichaue of y-told,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mayden</I> E. <I>&THORN;is m.] Sche</I> C; <I>&thorn;at</I> add. SNC. <I>ich&mdash;of] off whom I haue</I> E.</NOTE></L>
<L>Faire maide &yogh;he was &amp; bold<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A faire</I> SN. <I>wymman</I> ESN; om. C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="33">And fre y-boren;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fre] weel</I> EC.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Almayne &thorn;at emperur<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at] &thorn;e</I> ESNC.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hire hadde loued paramur<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Had hur</I> C. <I>hadde]</I> om. SN.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">Wel &thorn;ar be-foren.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wel]</I> om. E; <I>longe</I> add. SNC. <I>&thorn;ar] tyme</I> C; om. S.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ofte to hire fader a sente<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And ofte</I> C. <I>a]</I> om. C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And he him selue &thorn;eder wente<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he]</I> om. SNC. <I>he&mdash;&thorn;eder] for here loue &thorn;edyr he</I> E.</NOTE></L>
<L N="39">For hire sake;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Al for</I> E. <I>hire] own</I> add. C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ofte gernede hire to wiue:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ofte g.] Mechyl</I> (<I>Muche</I> SN) <I>he desyryd</I> ESNC; <I>to haue</I> add. C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e king for no &thorn;ing aliue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;e king] But they wolde not</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="42">Nolde hire him take.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wolde</I> SN. <I>Here nolde</I> E; <I>Hur to</I> C.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="4"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Si&thorn;e a &yogh;af hire to sire Gii,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I> (<I>And</I> SN) <I>se&thorn;&thorn;yn</I> ESN; <I>But</I> C. <I>a]</I> om. C.</NOTE></L>
<L>A stalword erl and hardi<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A]</I> om. E. <I>erl] man</I> ESN; <I>knyght</I> C. <I>and] an</I> add. SNC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">Of Sou&thorn;hamtoun.<MILESTONE UNIT="A folio" N="176a:2"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hamptoun</I> E.</NOTE></L>
<L>Man, whan he falle&thorn; in to elde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>But whanne men</I> (<I>he</I> SN) ESN. <I>fallen</I> E; <I>fel</I> SN. <I>to]</I> om. S. <I>A man oon</I> (?) <I>he ys holde</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Feble a wexe&thorn; and vnbelde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a w. and] and wexe</I> (<I>waxen</I> N) SN; <I>hem wur&thorn; and</I> E. <I>vnwylde</I> SN.</NOTE></L>
<L N="48">&THORN;our&yogh; ri&yogh;t resoun.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Be</I> ESN. <I>ri&yogh;t] grete</I> C; om. E.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So longe &thorn;ai &yogh;ede to gedres te bedde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to gedere</I> EN; <I>samen</I> S; om. C. <I>te] oon</I> add. C.</NOTE></L>
<L>A knaue child be-twene hem &thorn;ai hedde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Knaue] man</I> NC. <I>be-tw. h.] to gedere</I> ESNC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="51">Beues a het.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;at Beues heete</I> SN; <I>&amp; Befyse of Hamp|ton he hyght</I> C; <I>Beffs hy&yogh;te certayn</I> E.</NOTE></L>
<L>Faire child he was &amp; bolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A feire</I> SN. <I>child]</I> om. C. <I>was] had</I> (!) S. <I>&amp; b.] yn many folde</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>He nas boute seue winter olde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Than he</I> C. <I>was</I> EC. <I>winter] &yogh;ere</I> SNC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="54">Whan his fader was ded.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Tho</I> SN. <I>was slayn</I> E; <I>dyed yn fyght</I> C; <I>hym lete</I> SN.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e leuedi hire mis-be-&thorn;ou&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hire m.-be] a mysse hur be</I> C; <I>al a mys hur</I> (<I>she</I> S) SN.</NOTE></L>
<L>And meche a&yogh;en &thorn;e ri&yogh;t &yogh;he wrou&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And]</I> om. EC. <I>&thorn;e]</I> om. SN. <I>ri&yogh;t] lawe</I> C. <I>A&yogh;eyns &thorn;e ry&yogh;t meche</I> E.</NOTE></L>
<L N="57">In hire tour:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And cawsyd moche dolowre</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>'Me lord is olde &amp; may nou&yogh;t werche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lord] sche seyde</I> add. C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al dai him is leuer at cherche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Al d.]</I> om. C. <I>is him</I> S; <I>He hath</I> C. <I>leuer] to be</I> add. SNC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">&THORN;an in me bour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hadde ich itaken a &yogh;ong kni&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>But had</I> S.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ner nou&yogh;t brused in werre &amp; fi&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ner nou&yogh;t] hadde be nou&yogh;t</I> E: <I>was neuyr</I> C; <I>had not</I> (<I>neuer</I> N) <I>be</I> SN <I>prouyd</I> C. <I>werre &amp;]</I> om. ESNC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="63">Also he is,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he] now</I> add. ESN. <I>As now ys he</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>A wolde me louen dai and ni&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>louen] haue louyd</I> E. <I>dai a. n.] wi&thorn; al his my&yogh;t</I> ESN.</NOTE></L>
<L>Cleppen and kissen wi&thorn; al is mi&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Clyppyd &amp; kyssyd</I> E. <I>wi&thorn;&mdash;m.] be</I> (<I>bothe</I> N; om. S) <I>day &amp; ny&yogh;t</I> ESN.</NOTE></L>
<L N="66">And make me blis.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>maad</I> E.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="5"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I nel hit lete for no &thorn;inge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>But I</I> E. <I>woll</I> C. <I>hit] not</I> C; om. ESN. <I>lette</I> N; <I>leue</I> EC.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ich nel him to de&thorn;e bringe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;at] But</I> C; <I>Tyl &thorn;at</I> E. <I>wol</I> S; <I>wyll</I> C; om. E. <I>to</I> (om. E.) <I>de&thorn;e hym</I> ESNC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="69">Wi&thorn; sum braide!'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>braide] gyle</I> E; <I>rede</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Anon ri&yogh;t &thorn;at leuedi fer<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ri&yogh;t] tyde</I> C. <I>the</I> C. <I>lady</I> ESNC. <I>fer] free</I> NC; <I>cleer</I> E.</NOTE></L>
<L>To consaile clepede hir masager<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cleped to counsel</I> SN; <I>Callyd to here</I> E. <I>hir] a</I> E. <I>messanger</I> ESN. <I>A messengere clepyd sche</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="72">And to him saide:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>him] sche</I> add. C. <I>&THORN;at ylke whyle</I> E.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Maseger, do me surte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Mas.] y prey the</I> add. C. <I>surte] ensewre</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow nelt nou&yogh;t discure me<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nelt] wylt</I> C; <I>ne wylt</I> E; <I>shalt</I> SN. <I>not</I> N; <I>neuere</I> SC; om. E. <I>discrure</I> (!) A. <I>me dyskeuer</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="75">To no wi&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Neuer to</I> N.<Q><L><I>Of soche maters as y schall schewe to the,</I></L><L><I>And euyr my counsell kepe trewle</I></L><L><I>Bothe be day &amp; be nyght.</I> </L></Q>add. C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ow wilt, &thorn;at it so be,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And]</I> om. SC.</NOTE></L>
<L>I schel &thorn;e &yogh;eue gold and fe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wolle</I> SNC. <I>&yogh;eue] bo&thorn;e</I> add. ESN. <I>gold] londe</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="78">And make &thorn;e kni&yogh;t.'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e] a</I> add. C.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne answerde &thorn;e masager&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>answ.] bespak</I> E.</NOTE></L>
