<L>'I wile,' que&thorn; Beues ase snel,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wile q.] schall, seyde</I> C. <I>I&mdash;B.] B. seide</I> SN. <I>swell</I> (!) C.</NOTE></L>
<L>'&THORN;e leter bere treuliche &amp; wel;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;e&mdash;treul.] Bare</I> (!) <I>thy lettur feyrc</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Haue ich Arondel, me stede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Had</I> C. <I>me] gode</I> add. C.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">1246 f.:<Q><L><I>Haue y my stede Arundelle,</I></L><L><I>&THORN;y letter</I> (<I>wille y</I> (<I>I woll</I> N) <I>bere at nede.</I></L></Q> SN.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1248">Ich wile fare in to &thorn;at &thorn;ede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ich w. f.]</I> (<I>And wende</I> (<I>I wolde</I> C) <I>forth</I> SNC. <I>in&mdash;&thorn;ede] at thys nede</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Morgelai, me gode bronde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And] Haue y</I> SN. <I>Mordelay</I> (!) C. <I>gode]</I> om. SN.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich wile wende in to &thorn;at londe!'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wolde</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>King Ermin seide in is sawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sawes</I> S.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1252">&THORN;at ner no mesager is lawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ner] is</I> SN. <I>no] a&yogh;enst</I> S. <I>lawes</I> S.</NOTE></L>
<L>To ride vpon an heui stede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>an highe</I> S; <I>his</I> N.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at swiftli scholde don is nede:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>swiftli sch.] stilly shal</I> SN. <I>is] suche a</I> SN.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="60"></L>
<L>'Ac nim a li&yogh;ter hakenai<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac n.] But take</I> SN. <I>li&yogh;ter] lytel</I> SN.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1256">&amp; lef her &thorn;e swerd Morgelai,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lef h.] let</I> SN.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ow schelt come to Brademonde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to] king</I> add. SN.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sone wi&thorn; inne a lite stounde!'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wi&thorn; inne] in</I> S. <I>lytel</I> SN.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">1251&mdash;1258:<Q><L><I>What woldyst &thorn;ou do yn dede</I></L><L><I>Wyth Arondell, thy stede,</I></L><L><I>Or with thy swyrde Mordelay?</I></L><L><I>Take with the a lytull hakeney!</I></L></Q> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Benes an hakenai be-strit<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Syr B.</I> C. <I>an] dud &thorn;at</I> C. <I>&THORN;at hakenay B.</I> SN. <I>bestrod</I> SN; <I>bestryde</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1260">And in is wei for&thorn; a rit<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rit] rood</I> SN. <I>And for&thorn;e he goth with &thorn;at wryte</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bere&thorn; wi&thorn; him is owene de&thorn;,</L>
<L>Boute god him helpe, &thorn;at alle &thorn;ing se&thorn;!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>halp</I> (!) S. <I>&thorn;&iacute;g</I> (!) A.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">1261 f.:<Q><L><I>God helpe hym, &thorn;at beste may!</I></L><L><I>For&thorn;e he goyth yn hys way.</I></L></Q> C.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Terne we a&yogh;en, &thorn;ar we wer er,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>er]</I> om. C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1264">&amp; speke we of is em Saber!</L>
<L>After &thorn;at Beues was &thorn;us sold,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;us]</I> om. C.</NOTE></L>
<L>For him is hertte was euer cold;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For him]</I> om. C.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">1265 f.:<Q><L><I>Saberes hert was ful colde,</I></L><L><I>When &thorn;e</I> (<I>that</I> N) <I>childe was ferre ysolde</I></L></Q>; SN.</NOTE></L>
<L>A clepede to him his sone Terri<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to him his] his owne</I> SN. <I>Tarry</I> C; <I>Tyrrye</I> SN.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1268">And bad him wenden &amp; aspie<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&amp;] to</I> SN; <I>yn to</I> C. <I>assay</I> (!) C.</NOTE></L>
<L>In to eueri londe fer and ner,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In&mdash;londe] In hethenes</I> SN; <I>And seke Befyse</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whider him ladde &thorn;e maroner,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Whodur</I> C. <I>ladde] had sent</I> N. <I>mary|nere</I> SNC.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="61"></L>
<L>And seide: 'Sone, &thorn;ow ert min owen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Son, he seide</I> SN. <I>owe</I> S.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1272">Wel &thorn;ow canst &thorn;e lord knowen!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wel] For</I> SN. <I>&thorn;yn</I> S. <I>lord] wel</I> add. SN. <I>knowe</I> S.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich hote &thorn;e, sone, in alle manere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I &thorn;e hoote</I> S; <I>He hote</I> (!) N. <I>sone]</I> om. SN.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow him seche &thorn;is seue &yogh;er:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;is]</I> om. SN.
<Q><L><I>In which lond so</I> (<I>that</I> N) <I>&thorn;ou wende,</I></L><L><I>Spendyng ynow&yogh;e</I> (<I>euer</I> N) <I>y shal</I> (<I>wol</I> N) <I>&thorn;e sende,</I></L><L><I>Where &thorn;ou be in eny londe,</I></L><L><I>Euer &thorn;ou sende me &thorn;y sonde:</I></L></Q> add. SN.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">1271&mdash;1274:<Q><L><I>Palmars wede &thorn;ou schalt were,</I></L><L><I>So mayst &thorn;ou &thorn;e bettur aftur hym speer,</I></L><L><I>And euyr whodur &thorn;at &thorn;ou wende,</I></L><L><I>Golde ynogh y schall the sende.'</I></L><L><I>Tho seyde Tarry: 'Be the trynyte,</I></L><L><I>I schall hym seke yn many a cuntre.</I></L></Q> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich wile feche him, mowe &thorn;ow him fynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>feche&mdash;&thorn;ow] him seche tyl y</I> SN. <I>wile&mdash;&thorn;ow him] schall assay hym to</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1276">&THORN;ou&yogh; he be bi-&yogh;ende Ynde!'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;ou&yogh;] If that</I> C. <I>bi-&yogh;.] in &thorn;e lond of</I> SN.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">1276 put before 1275 C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Terri, is sone, is for&thorn; ifare,<NOTE PLACE="foot">(<I>Now</I> add. C) <I>for&thorn;</I> (<I>in his way</I> (om. C) <I>Tyrry is fare</I> SNC.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="A folio" N="183a:2"></L>
<L>Beues a sou&yogh;te eueri whare;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>B.&mdash;eu.] And sou&yogh;t</I> (<I>sekyth</I> C) <I>B. wyde</I> SNC.
<Q><L><I>Now ys Tarry passyd the see:</I></L><L><I>God kepe hym for hys pete!</I></L><L><I>And soght Befyse thorow Tuskey,</I></L><L><I>Thorow Armony and Assay,</I></L></Q> add. C.</NOTE></L>
<L>In al he&thorn;enes nas toun non,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al]</I> om. C. <I>nas] &thorn;er was</I> C; <I>nan</I> (!) A.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1280">&THORN;at cristene man mi&yogh;te &thorn;er in gon,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>men</I> SNC. <I>mi&yogh;te] had</I> SN. <I>&thorn;er]</I> om. SNC. <I>in]</I> om. N.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne ha&thorn; Beues in isou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he] Tyrry</I> SN. <I>had</I> SN. <I>in]</I> om. SN. <I>But Tarry Befyse soght</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac he ne kou&thorn;e finde him nou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac] But</I> SNC. <I>kou&thorn;e] my&yogh;t</I> SN. <I>he&mdash;finde] &yogh;yt he founde</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>So hit be fel vpon a cas,</L>
<L N="1284">&THORN;at Terri com beside Damas;
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="62"></L>
<L>&amp; ase he com for&thorn; be &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>A sat and dinede in a wede</L>
<L>Vnder a faire medle tre,</L>
<L N="1288">&THORN;at sire Beues gan of-<I>see.</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>see]</I> om. (!) A.</NOTE></L>
<L>'Sire,' que&thorn; Terri, 'for sein Iuline!</L>
<L>Is it &thorn;e wille, com nere &amp; dine!'</L>
<L N="1291">Beues was of-hongred sore</L>
<L>And kou&thorn;e him gret &thorn;ank &thorn;er fore,</L>
<L>For twei dawes he hadde ride</L>
<L>Fastande in &thorn;at ilche wede.
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="63"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e palmer nas nou&yogh;t wi&thorn;outen store,</L>
<L N="1296">Inou&yogh; a leide him be-fore,</L>
<L>Bred and flesc out of is male</L>
<L>And of his flaketes win &amp; ale</L>
<L>Whan Beues hadde eten gret foisoun,</L>
<L N="1300">Terri askede at sire Beuoun,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if a herde telle &yogh;ong or olde</L>
<L>Of a child, &thorn;at &thorn;eder was solde:</L>
<L>His name was i-hote Beuoun,</L>
<L N="1304">I-bore a was at Sou&thorn;-Hamtoun.
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="64"></L>
<L>Beues be-held Terri &amp; lou&yogh;</L>
<L>&amp; seide, a knew &thorn;at child wel inou&yogh;:</L>
<L>'Hit is nou&yogh;t,' a seide, 'gon longe,</L>
<L>I se&yogh; &thorn;e Sarsins &thorn;at child an-honge!'</L>
<L N="1309">Terri fel &thorn;er doun and swou&yogh;,</L>
<L>His her, his clo&thorn;es he al to-drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Whan he awok and speke mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="1312">Sore a wep and sore si&yogh;te</L>
<L>And seide: 'Allas, &thorn;at he was boren!</L>
<L>Is me lord Beues for-loren?'
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="65"></L>
<L>Beues tok him vp at &thorn;at cas</L>
<L N="1316">And gan him for to solas:</L>
<L>'Wend hom,' a seide, 'to &thorn;e contre!</L>
<L>Sai &thorn;e frendes so ichaue &thorn;e:</L>
<L N="1319">&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ow him seche &thorn;es seue &yogh;er,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow worst &thorn;at child neuer &thorn;e ner!'</L>
<L>Terri on Beues be-held<MILESTONE UNIT="A folio" N="183b:1"></L>
<L>And se&yogh; &thorn;e boiste wi&thorn; a scheld.</L>
<L>'Me &thorn;enke&thorn;, &thorn;ow ert a masager,</L>
<L N="1324">&THORN;at in &thorn;is londe walkes her;</L>
<L>Icham a clerk and to scole &yogh;ede:</L>
<L>Sire, let me &thorn;e letter rede,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ow mi&yogh;t haue gret doute,</L>
<L N="1328">&THORN;in owene de&thorn; to bere aboute!'
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="66"></L>
<L>Beues seide, ich vnder-stonde:</L>
<L>'He, &thorn;at me tok &thorn;is letter an honde,</L>
<L>He ne wolde <I>loue</I> me non o&thorn;er,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>loue]</I> om. A.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1332">&THORN;an ich were is owene bro&thorn;er.'</L>
<L>Beues him &thorn;ankede &amp; &thorn;us hii delde:</L>
<L>Terri wente hom and telde</L>
<L>His fader Saber in &thorn;e ilde of Wi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1336">How him tolde a gentil kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Sarsins hadde Beues for-fare</L>
<L>And hangede him, while he was &thorn;are.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saber wep and made drem,</L>
<L N="1340">For he was &thorn;e childes em,</L>
<L>And ech &yogh;er on a dai certaine</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;emperur of Almaine</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a wel gret baronage</L>
<L N="1344">A cleimede his eritage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Let we now ben is em Saber</L>
<L>&amp; speke of Beues, &thorn;e maseger!</L>
<L>For&thorn; him wente sire Beuoun,</L>
<L N="1348">Til a com to Dames toun;
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="67"></L>
<L>Aboute &thorn;e time of middai</L>
<L>Out of a mameri a sai</L>
<L>Sarasins come gret foisoun,</L>
<L N="1352">&THORN;at hadde anoured here Mahoun.
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="68"></L>
<L>Beues of is palfrei ali&yogh;te</L>
<L>And ran to her mameri ful ri&yogh;te</L>
<L>And slou&yogh; here prest, &thorn;at &thorn;er was in,</L>
<L N="1356">And &thorn;rew here godes in &thorn;e fen</L>
<L>And lou&yogh; hem alle &thorn;er to scorn.</L>
<L>On ascapede and at-orn</L>
<L>In at &thorn;e castel &yogh;ete,</L>
<L N="1360">Ase &thorn;e king sat at &thorn;e mete.
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="69"></L>
<L>'Sire' seide &thorn;is man at &thorn;e frome,</L>
<L>'Her is icome a corsede gome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;rowe&thorn; our godes in &thorn;e fen</L>
<L N="1364">And sle&thorn; al oure men;</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="A folio" N="183b:2">Vnne&thorn;e i scapede among &thorn;at &thorn;ring,</L>
<L>For to bringe &thorn;e tiding!'</L>
<L>Brademond quakede at &thorn;e bord</L>
<L>&amp; seide: '&THORN;at is Beues, me lord!'</L>
<L N="1369">Beues wente in at &thorn;e castel &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>His hors he lefte &thorn;er ate</L>
<L>And wente for&thorn; in to &thorn;e halle</L>
<L N="1372">And grete hem in &thorn;is maner alle:</L>
<L>'God, &thorn;at made &thorn;is world al ronde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al r.] aronde</I> (!) A.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e saue, sire king Brademond,</L>
<L>And ek alle &thorn;ine fere,</L>
<L N="1376">&THORN;at i se now here,</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at ilche blessing</L>
<L>Like&thorn; &thorn;e ri&yogh;t no&thorn;ing,
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>Mahoun, &thorn;at is god &thorn;in,</L>
<L N="1380">Teruagaunt &amp; Apolin,</L>
<L>&THORN;e blessi and di&yogh;te</L>
<L>Be alle here mi&yogh;te!</L>
<L>Lo her, &thorn;e king Ermin</L>
<L N="1384">&THORN;e sente &thorn;is letter in parchemin,</L>
<L>And ase &thorn;e letter &thorn;e telle&thorn; to,</L>
<L>A bad, &thorn;ow scholdest swi&thorn;e do!'</L>
<L>Beues kneuled &amp; nolde nou&yogh;t stonde</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;af vp is de&thorn; wi&thorn; is owene honde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Brademond quakede al for drede,</L>
<L N="1390">He vndede &thorn;e letter &amp; gan to rede</L>
<L>And fond iwriten in &thorn;at felle,</L>
<L>How &thorn;at he scholde Beues aquelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne seide Brademond to twenti king,</L>
<L>&THORN;at were &thorn;at dai at is gistning,</L>
<L>A spak wi&thorn; tresoun &amp; wi&thorn; gile:</L>
<L N="1396">'Arise&thorn; vp,' he sede 'a while,</L>
<L>Euerich of &yogh;ow fro &thorn;e bord,</L>
<L>And wolcome&thorn; &yogh;our kende lord!'
