<L N="1399">Alle hii gonnen vp ri&yogh;t stonde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">1283&mdash;1399:<Q><L>(<I>Tyll hyt befelle vpon a day,</I></L><L><I>As ye the sothe here may.</I></L><L><I>Keste we now of Tarrys fare</I></L><L><I>And of Befyse speke we mare!</I></L><L N="5"><I>Syr Befyse rode a gode pase</I></L><L><I>Toward the cyte of Damaske.</I></L><L><I>Two dayes he rode ryght,</I></L><L><I>Or he of hys hors lyght,</I></L><L><I>But as faste as he myght ryde</I></L><L N="10"><I>Tyll &thorn;e thrydde morne tyde.</I></L><L><I>Be &thorn;at lyste Befyse to ete &amp; drynke,</I></L><L><I>As a wery man aftur swynke</I></L><L><I>To slepe he lyste, as &thorn;e romans tellys;</I></L><L><I>For he my&yogh;t gete nothyng ellys,</I></L><L N="15"><I>Befyse leyde hym to slepe &thorn;at stounde,</I></L><L><I>And hys hors ete vpon &thorn;e grounde.</I></L><L><I>When he was wakyd of hys slepe,</I></L><L><I>Vpon hys hors can he lepe.</I> C; om. SN.</L><L><I>Sir B. rood four&thorn;</I> (om. C.) <I>on</I> (<I>in</I> N) <I>hys</I> (<I>&thorn;e</I> S) <I>way,</I></L><L N="20"><I>He nold</I> (<I>wolde</I> C) <I>make noon delay;</I></L><L><I>In a forest long and brood</I></L><L><I>On</I> (<I>Vpon</I> C) <I>his hors forth he rood.</I></L><L><I>On (Vpon</I> C) <I>his ry&yogh;t honde he sey&yogh;e him</I> (om. C) <I>nere</I></L><L><I>A palmer sit</I> (<I>syttyng</I> C) <I>at his</I> (om. C) <I>dynere,</I></L><L N="25"><I>Al oon he sat, as he was born,</I></L><L>(<I>And</I> add. C; <I>Good</I> add. N) <I>mete and drynke was</I> (<I>he had</I> N; om. C) <I>him byforn,</I></L><L>(<I>He sate vnder a feire tree,</I></L><L><I>(Mete &amp; drynke for knyghtes thre,</I> C)</L><L><I>While he</I> (<I>&thorn;ey</I> C) <I>wolde</I> (<I>sitte and</I> (om. S) <I>&thorn;ere</I> (<I>&thorn;er at</I> C) <I>be.</I></L><L N="30">(<I>iii. fowles</I> (<I>There</I> C) <I>he hadde to</I> (<I>at</I> C) <I>his dynere,</I></L><L>(<I>&THORN;at men calle colueres</I> (<I>The curlews &thorn;at be clepyd</I> C) <I>here;</I></L><L><I>In