</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e king Yuore him ros amorwe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;e]</I> om. SNC. <I>him]</I> om. SNC. <I>am.] on the</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>In his hertte was meche sorwe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>his&mdash;meche] greet care and in</I> (om. S) SNC.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000281.tif" N="195"></L>
<L>He let of sende an hi&yogh;ing<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He] And</I> S. <I>let of-s.] sent after</I> SNC. <I>in</I> SN. <I>an h.] lordyngys</I> C.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="3931"></L>
<L N="4112">&THORN;retti amirales &amp; ten king.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;retti] XV</I> SNC. <I>ten] XV</I> SN; om. C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai armede hem in yrene wede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;ai] And</I> SNC. <I>them</I> C. <I>in y. w.] prest</I> (om. C) <I>to fy&yogh;t</I> SNC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4114">To Ermonie he gan hem lede.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Erm.] Ambyfort</I> SN; <I>Amford</I> C. <I>he&mdash;lede] &thorn;ey went ry&yogh;t</I> SNC.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hii pi&yogh;te pauiliouns &amp; bente ginne,</L>
<L>For to be-sege hem &thorn;er inne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">4115 f. om. SNC.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="3936"></L>
<L>And Yuore clepede at &thorn;at cas<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And] King</I> SNC. <I>clep.]</I> om. SNC. <I>at] yn</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4118">Morable and sire Iudas.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cleped Arabele</I> SN; <I>Clepyd</I> C. <I>sire]</I> om. SN. <I>and s.] to hym marschall</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>'Rede&thorn; me,' a seide, 'ari&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Rede</I> SNC. <I>me] now</I> add. SN.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich mai vnder-stonde &thorn;is fi&yogh;t<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="3940"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;if] that</I> add. C. <I>mai] shal</I> SNC. <I>vnd.] take</I> SN; <I>do</I> C. <I>&thorn;is] ylke</I> add. SN.</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;en Beues of Hamtoun,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A&yogh;ens</I> S; <I>sir</I> add. SN.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4122">&THORN;at is so stout a baroun!'</L>
<L>'We rede&thorn; meintene &yogh;our parti!'</L>
<L>He lep to hors &amp; gan to crie:<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="3944">
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="196"></L>
<L>'Sire Beues of Hamtoun,' a sede,</L>
<L><I>'&THORN;ou</I> hauest &thorn;ar inne gret ferede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;ou] &THORN;at</I> (!) A.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ich her oute mani stout kni&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ich] haue</I> add. SNC. <I>oute]</I> om. SNC. <I>stout] a</I> NC; om. S.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4128">Ichaue brou&yogh;t wi&thorn; me to fi&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Seker and bolde (for to (and prest to</I> N; <I>yn euery</I> C) <I>fy&yogh;t</I> SNC.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;if we bataile schel abide,<NOTE PLACE="foot">4122&mdash;29:<Q><L><I>'A nobel kny&yogh;t of renoun,</I></L><L><I>'We reede &thorn;er to, (we seye (thei seiden</I> N) <I>alle!'</I></L><L><I>B. of Hampton he (&thorn;ei</I> N) <I>gan calle,</I></L><L><I>Swythe lowde he gan crye:</I></L><L><I>'&THORN;ou hast here a</I> (om. N) <I>grete cheualrye,</I></L></Q> SN.<Q><L><I>That ys a man of grete renown.'</I></L><L><I>'We assent ther to,' they seyde all,</I></L><L><I>And to syr Befyse can they calle;</I></L><L><I>Swythe lowde they can crye:</I></L><L><I>'Thou haste a grete compenye,'</I></L></Q> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gret slau&yogh;ter wor&thorn; in ei&thorn;er side.<NOTE PLACE="foot">4129 f. om. SNC.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="3950"></L>
<L>Wiltow graunte be &thorn;en helue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be</I> &thorn;. <I>h.] in thy behalf (half</I> N) SN; <I>me on thy party</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ich and &thorn;ow mote fi&yogh;te vs selue?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;ow and y by oure self</I> SN; <I>For to fyght thou and y</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4133">&YOGH;if &thorn;ow slest me in bataile,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>me slee (slo</I> NC) SNC. <I>in] pleyn</I> add. SN.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al min onour, wi&thorn; outen faile,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wi&thorn; o.] saunz</I> SNC.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich &thorn;e graunte &thorn;our&yogh; &amp; &thorn;our&yogh;,<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="3955"></L>
<L N="4136">Bo&thorn;e in cite and in bour&yogh;!'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>citees</I> N.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">4135 f. om. S.<Q><L><I>The romauns tellith, saunz faile,</I></L><L><I>B. him grauntid that bataile.</I></L></Q> add. N.<Q><L><I>B. him graunted &thorn;at bataile,</I></L><L><I>&THORN;e romaunce telle&thorn;, saunz faile.</I></L></Q> add. S.<Q><L><I>As hyt ys yn romans tolde,</I></L><L><I>Befyse grauntyd that batayle bolde.</I></L></Q> add. S.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here glouen &thorn;ai gonne vp holde<MILESTONE UNIT="A folio" N="198b:1"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ther</I> C. <I>gloues</I> SNC. <I>gonne] dud</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;at forward, &thorn;at Yuor tolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at] &thorn;e</I> SN. <I>forw.] maner</I> C. <I>&thorn;at Y.] &thorn;at y &yogh;ow</I> SN; <I>as they</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And armede hem in armes bri&yogh;te</L>
<L>And lopen to horse anon ri&yogh;te<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="3960"></L>
<L N="4141">In an yle vnder &thorn;at cite,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar &thorn;at scholde &thorn;e bataile be.<NOTE PLACE="foot">4139&mdash;4142:<Q><L><I>Her armour (&thorn;ey gan (gan thei</I> N) <I>to hem tee</I></L><L><I>And to hors lepen hee.</I></L></Q> SN;<Q><L><I>They armyd them soone yn hye</I></L><L><I>And starte to ther horsys lustyly.</I></L></Q> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;at water &thorn;ai gonne ride,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at] &thorn;e</I> SN.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hire godes &thorn;ai bede in ei&thorn;er side;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>god</I> SN. <I>bede in] prayde in (on</I> N) SN.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">4143 f.:<Q><L><I>And to ther goddys &thorn;e hethen party prayed,</I></L><L><I>And so dud Befyse to hys lorde on hys syde.</I></L></Q> C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Beues bad help to Marie sone<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="3965"></L>
<L>And king Yuor to sein Mahoune;</L>
