<L N="240"><I>In to chaumbre sere B. is goo,</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>To hur he (they</I> C) <I>went hastely (yn hye</I> C) NC.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>And in hys armys hys wyff he tas,</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And] Sur B.</I> NC. <I>hys w.] hur</I> NC. <I>he]</I> om. N. <I>lace</I> N; <I>tase</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>And kyste here ffayre in &thorn;at caas.</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ffayre]</I> om. NC. <I>in] at</I> NC.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>For so&thorn;e, &thorn;ey deyden bo&thorn;e in ffere,</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For s.] And</I> N; <I>And there</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>As sei&thorn; &thorn;e romaunce on &thorn;is manere.</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>As&mdash;&thorn;is] The kyng</I> (<I>nolde in</I> (<I>wolde on</I> C) <I>no</I> NC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="245"><I>Alle &thorn;e ffolk off &thorn;at cyte</I></L>
<L><I>Wolden nou&yogh;t suffren hem beryyd be</I></L>
<L><I>Ne in no er&thorn;e ffor to be leyd,</I></L>
<L><I>But euerychon ry&yogh;t wi&thorn; a breyd</I></L>
<L><I>Off seynt Lauraunce a cherche made &thorn;ere,</I></L>
<L N="250"><I>Off gold &thorn;ey maden &thorn;e hey&yogh;e awtere</I></L>
<L><I>And beryeden hem bo&thorn;e in same:</I></L>
<L><I>Off hem comi&thorn; boote to blynde &amp; lame.</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">245&mdash;52. <I>That thei in erthe buried were; Of seint Laurence he lete a chapel rere, And of gold made a chist gay, And bothe hur bodies &thorn;er in lay; Men tellith bothe in gest &amp; ryme, Thei were leide in maner of shryne.</I> N. <I>That they yn erthe beryed were, For a chapell of seynt Laurens he wyll rere, Of golde he made &thorn;e ryche couere, There are &thorn;ey beryed bo&thorn;e yn fere.</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>An hous &thorn;ey maden off relygyoun,</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And a</I> N. <I>he made</I> C; <I>maad</I> N.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Euere to syngen ffor sere Beffoun</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>To synge ever</I> N.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255"><I>And ffor Iosyan, &thorn;at lady ffree:</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ffor]</I> om. C. <I>&thorn;at l.] the</I> NC.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>God on here soulys now haue pete!</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on] of</I> N. <I>ther</I> C. <I>now]</I> om. NC.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>And on Arundel, hys goode stede,</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on] also for</I> NC. <I>hys g. s.]</I> om. NC.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>&yogh;iff men for hors scholden synge or rede.</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>men] that</I> N. <I>for] an</I> add. C. <I>schol.&mdash;rede] men may bid wel</I> N; <I>prey schall</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>&THORN;us endi&thorn; sere Bcffs off Hamptoun,</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sere]</I> om. NC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="260"><I>&THORN;at was so noble a baroun. Amen.</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so n. a] king and nobil</I> N. <I>&THORN;at&mdash;a] Gentyll knyght &amp; bolde</I> C. <I>Al that of his life haue</I> (<I>herd inviron</I> (<I>harde</I> C), <I>God yeve hare</I> (<I>ther</I> C) <I>sowlis</I> (<I>of</I> add. C) <I>heven pardon</I> (<I>parte</I> C), <I>And</I> (<I>that we were al</I> (<I>to be</I> C) <I>of suche</I> (<I>as grete</I> C) <I>renoun, As</I> (<I>euyr</I> add. C) <I>was B. of Hamptoun.</I> add. NC. <I>Amen. Here endith Bevys of Hampton.</I> add. N.</NOTE></L>
</LG></Q> E.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his barouns gode &amp; hende;</L>
<L>&amp; Terry to Aumber&thorn;e gan wende,<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="4404"></L>
<L>And Beues wente wi&thorn; oute dwelling</L>
<L>In to Mombraunt, &thorn;ar he was king;</L>
<L N="4587">Wi&thorn; him wente Iosian, is quene,</L>
<L>&amp; leuede wi&thorn; oute treie &amp; tene</L>
<L>Twenti &yogh;er, so sai&thorn; &thorn;e bok.<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="4409"></L>
<L>&THORN;anne swiche siknesse &thorn;e leuedi tok,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world &yogh;he moste wende;</L>
<L N="4592">Gii, hire sone, &yogh;he gan of-sende,</L>
<L>And Terry, &thorn;e riche king,</L>
<L>For to ben at here parting.</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ai were alle &thorn;are,<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="4415"></L>
<L N="4596">To his stable Beues gan fare;</L>
<L>Arondel a fond &thorn;ar ded,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer hadde be gode at nede;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar fore him was swi&thorn;e wo,</L>
<L>In to chaumber he gan go<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="4420">
<PB REF="00000303.tif" N="217"></L>
<L N="4601">&amp; se&yogh; losian drawe to dede:</L>
<L>Him was wo a moste nede,</L>
<L>And er her body be-gan to colde,</L>
<L N="4604">In is armes he gan hire folde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar hii deide bo&thorn;e ifere.<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="4425"></L>
<L>Here sone ne wolde in non manere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hii in er&thorn;e beried were:</L>
<L N="4608">Of sein Lauarauns he let arere</L>
<L>A faire chapel of marbel fin,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was ikast wi&thorn; queint engin;<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="4430"></L>
<L>Of gold he made an hi&yogh; cornere</L>
<L N="4612">And leide &thorn;em &thorn;ar in bo&thorn;e ifere.</L>
<L>An hous he made of riligioun,</L>
<L>For to singe for sire Beuoun</L>
<L>And ek for Iosian &thorn;e fre:<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="4435"></L>
<L N="4616">God on here saules haue pite!
<PB REF="00000304.tif" N="218"></L>
<L>&amp; also for Arondel,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if men for eni hors bidde schel.</L>
<L N="4619">&THORN;us ende&thorn; Beues of Hamtoun:</L>
<L>God &yogh;eue vs alle is benesoun!<MILESTONE UNIT="Turnbull line" N="4440"></L>
<CLOSER>Amen.</CLOSER>
</LG>


